ome characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Milly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Walloon: habitational name from Billy, the name of several places mainly in the northern part of France. The placename is from Gallo-Roman <i>Billiacum</i>, from the Gallic personal name <i>Billios</i> (from Latin <i>Billius</i>) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","English: habitational name from any of several places called Billy, such as Billy Row in Brancepeth (Durham), or Billy Farm in Somerset.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Billy</i>, a pet form of <i>Mabel</i> or <i>Sibyl</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bily","meanings":["Czech (<b>Bílý</b> and <b>Bilý</b>) and Slovak (<b>Bilý</b>, also <b>Bíly</b>); Ukrainian and Rusyn (standard transliteration <b>Bilyy</b>): nickname for a fair-haired man, from Czech (and Slovak dialect) <i>bílý</i>, Ukrainian and Rusyn <i>bilyy</i> ‘white’. Compare   Bila   and   Billie   3."]}]},{"name":"Estefania","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Stephen</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stephen","meanings":["Usual English spelling of the name of the first Christian martyr (Acts 6–7), whose feast is accordingly celebrated next after Christ's own (  26 December ). His name is derived from the Greek word <i>stephanos</i> ‘garland, crown’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Estefania de Milly was born after 1145, in France as the daughter of Philip de Milly. She had at least 1 son and 5 daughters with Renaud I de Châtillon Prince d